### For Loop in Rust

The `for` loop in Rust is used to iterate over items in a collection or range. It is the most idiomatic looping construct.

---

### For Loop Forms

| Form | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `for x in iterable { }` | Basic iteration |
| `for (i, x) in iter.enumerate() { }` | With index |
| `for x in 0..10 { }` | Range (exclusive end) |
| `for x in 0..=10 { }` | Range (inclusive end) |

---

### Examples

```rust
// Range iteration
for i in 0..5 {
    println!("{}", i);  // 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
}

// Inclusive range
for i in 1..=3 {
    println!("{}", i);  // 1, 2, 3
}

// Iterating over a vector
let v = vec![10, 20, 30];
for val in &v {
    println!("val: {}", val);
}

// With enumerate
for (index, value) in v.iter().enumerate() {
    println!("v[{}] = {}", index, value);
}
```

> **Key Point:** The `for` loop consumes the iterator. Use `&collection` or `collection.iter()` to borrow elements instead of taking ownership.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    let numbers = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

    println!("Squares:");
    for num in &numbers {
        println!("{} squared = {}", num, num * num);
    }

    let mut sum = 0;
    for i in 1..=10 {
        sum += i;
    }
    println!("Sum 1 to 10: {}", sum);
}
